				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} ACC = \frac{TP+TN}{TP+FP+TN+FN} \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Accuracy is not a good metric to use when the dataset has the class imbalance problem. So in this work F1-score is also used to evaluate the performance. It is the weighted harmonic mean of recall and precision and is given by the Eq. 17.17F1-score=2∗TP2∗TP+FN+FP\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} F1-score =\frac{2*TP}{2*TP+FN+FP} \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Area under operator curve (AUC) is the area underneath the receiver operator curve (ROC) that calculates the model’s ability to discriminate samples between positive and negative classes. The value of AUC ranges between 0 and 1. AUC value 0 indicates a poor classification and AUC value 1 indicates a perfect classification.
